        {
          "title": "Introduction to Neural Networks",
          "slug": "intro-neural-networks",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Introduction to Neural Networks\n\n## What is a Neuron?\n\nA biological neuron receives electrical signals from many other neurons through its **dendrites**, processes them in the **cell body**, and fires an output signal through its **axon** when the accumulated input exceeds a threshold.\n\nAn artificial neuron mimics this: it takes a vector of inputs **x**, multiplies each by a learned weight **w**, sums them up, adds a bias term **b**, and passes the result through an **activation function** σ:\n\n```\noutput = σ(w₁x₁ + w₂x₂ + ... + wₙxₙ + b)\n       = σ(wᵀx + b)\n```\n\nThe weights encode *how important* each input is; the bias shifts the activation threshold.\n\n## Layers: Input, Hidden, Output\n\nNeural networks are organized into **layers**:\n\n- **Input layer**: Raw data features (pixel values, word embeddings, sensor readings). No computation happens here.\n- **Hidden layers**: Each neuron applies a linear transformation followed by a nonlinearity. These layers learn abstract representations.\n- **Output layer**: Produces the final prediction — a probability distribution for classification, or a real value for regression.\n\nA network with at least one hidden layer is called a **Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP)**.\n\n```python\nimport torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\nclass SimpleMLP(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, input_dim, hidden_dim, output_dim):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.layer1 = nn.Linear(input_dim, hidden_dim)\n        self.layer2 = nn.Linear(hidden_dim, output_dim)\n        self.relu = nn.ReLU()\n\n    def forward(self, x):\n        x = self.relu(self.layer1(x))  # hidden layer with ReLU\n        return self.layer2(x)           # output layer (no activation for regression)\n```\n\n## Activation Functions\n\nWithout nonlinear activations, stacking layers would collapse into a single linear transformation — no matter how deep. Activations introduce the nonlinearity that lets networks approximate complex functions.\n\n| Function | Formula | Properties |\n|----------|---------|------------|\n| **Sigmoid** | σ(x) = 1/(1+e⁻ˣ) | Outputs (0,1), saturates → vanishing gradients |\n| **Tanh** | tanh(x) = (eˣ−e⁻ˣ)/(eˣ+e⁻ˣ) | Outputs (−1,1), zero-centered, still saturates |\n| **ReLU** | max(0, x) | Fast, no saturation for x>0, can \"die\" |\n| **GELU** | x·Φ(x) | Smooth ReLU, used in Transformers |\n\n**ReLU** is the default choice for hidden layers in practice because it's computationally cheap and avoids the vanishing gradient problem for positive activations.\n\n## The Forward Pass\n\nData flows **forward** through the network: input → hidden layers → output. Each layer computes:\n\n```\nhˡ = σ(Wˡ hˡ⁻¹ + bˡ)\n```\n\nwhere **hˡ** is the activation vector at layer *l*, **Wˡ** is the weight matrix, and **bˡ** is the bias vector.\n\n```python\n# Manual forward pass (pedagogical)\ndef forward_pass(x, layers):\n    h = x\n    for W, b, activation in layers:\n        z = W @ h + b    # linear transformation\n        h = activation(z) # nonlinearity\n    return h\n```\n\n## Universal Approximation Theorem\n\nA key theoretical result: a feedforward network with **one hidden layer** containing enough neurons can approximate **any continuous function** on a compact domain to arbitrary precision. This tells us that expressivity isn't the bottleneck — learning the right weights is.\n\nIn practice, **depth** (more layers) is far more efficient than width (more neurons per layer) for learning hierarchical features. A 10-layer network with 100 neurons per layer typically outperforms a 1-layer network with 10,000 neurons.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Neurons are weighted sums followed by a nonlinear activation\n- Layers stack transformations to build hierarchical representations\n- The forward pass computes predictions by propagating data through all layers\n- Depth enables efficient representation of complex, hierarchical patterns\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Gradient descent, how neural networks learn](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IHZwWFHWa-w) by 3Blue1Brown — the companion video to the one above, showing how gradient descent actually adjusts weights to minimize the loss function.\n",
          "summary": "Neural networks are computational graphs of interconnected nodes that learn to map inputs to outputs through layered transformations.",
          "concepts": [
            "neurons",
            "layers",
            "activation functions",
            "forward pass"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "aircAruvnKk",
          "video_title": "But what is a neural network? | 3Blue1Brown",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
