        {
          "title": "Backpropagation & Gradient Descent",
          "slug": "backpropagation",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Backpropagation & Gradient Descent\n\n## The Learning Problem\n\nA neural network's weights start random. Learning means adjusting them so the network's outputs match the true labels. We need a way to measure error and update every weight accordingly — even weights deep in the network that don't directly touch the output.\n\n**Backpropagation** solves this by efficiently computing gradients using the **chain rule** from calculus.\n\n## Loss Functions\n\nThe loss function quantifies how wrong our predictions are:\n\n- **Mean Squared Error (regression)**: L = (1/n) Σ (ŷᵢ − yᵢ)²\n- **Cross-Entropy (classification)**: L = −Σ yᵢ log(ŷᵢ)\n\nThe goal is to minimize L by adjusting weights W and biases b.\n\n## The Chain Rule\n\nIf L depends on z, and z depends on w, then:\n\n```\n∂L/∂w = (∂L/∂z) · (∂z/∂w)\n```\n\nFor a network with layers, the gradient of the loss with respect to weight **Wˡ** in layer *l* is computed by chaining gradients backward from the output:\n\n```\n∂L/∂Wˡ = δˡ · (hˡ⁻¹)ᵀ\n```\n\nwhere **δˡ** is the \"error signal\" at layer *l*, computed recursively:\n\n```\nδˡ = ((Wˡ⁺¹)ᵀ δˡ⁺¹) ⊙ σ'(zˡ)\n```\n\n## Forward Pass → Backward Pass\n\n**Forward pass** (storing intermediate values):\n```python\nz1 = W1 @ x + b1\nh1 = relu(z1)          # save z1 for backward\nz2 = W2 @ h1 + b2\noutput = softmax(z2)\nloss = cross_entropy(output, y)\n```\n\n**Backward pass** (propagating gradients):\n```python\n# Output layer gradient\ndL_dz2 = output - y_onehot\n\n# Hidden layer gradient (chain rule)\ndL_dh1 = W2.T @ dL_dz2\ndL_dz1 = dL_dh1 * relu_grad(z1)   # element-wise\n\n# Weight gradients\ndL_dW2 = dL_dz2 @ h1.T\ndL_dW1 = dL_dz1 @ x.T\n```\n\nPyTorch automates this with `loss.backward()`.\n\n## Gradient Descent\n\nOnce we have gradients, we update weights to reduce the loss:\n\n```\nW ← W − η · ∂L/∂W\n```\n\nwhere **η** (eta) is the **learning rate** — a hyperparameter controlling step size.\n\n### Variants\n\n| Variant | Update Rule | Notes |\n|---------|------------|-------|\n| **Batch GD** | Full dataset gradient | Stable but slow |\n| **Stochastic GD (SGD)** | One sample at a time | Noisy but fast |\n| **Mini-batch SGD** | Batch of 32-256 samples | Best of both worlds |\n\n```python\noptimizer = torch.optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.01)\noptimizer.zero_grad()   # clear old gradients\nloss.backward()         # compute new gradients\noptimizer.step()        # update weights\n```\n\n## The Vanishing Gradient Problem\n\nFor deep networks, gradients can **vanish** (shrink exponentially) as they propagate backward through many layers. With sigmoid activations, σ'(x) ≤ 0.25, so multiplying gradients across 10 layers gives (0.25)¹⁰ ≈ 0.000001 — essentially zero.\n\n**Solutions**:\n- Use **ReLU** activations (gradient = 1 for positive inputs)\n- **Residual connections** (skip connections) in ResNets\n- **Batch normalization** to stabilize gradient magnitudes\n- Careful weight initialization (Xavier, He)\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Backprop applies the chain rule to efficiently compute all gradients in one backward pass\n- Gradient descent moves weights in the direction that reduces the loss\n- Learning rate is critical: too large → divergence; too small → slow convergence\n- Vanishing gradients are the main challenge for very deep networks\n",
          "summary": "Backpropagation efficiently computes gradients of the loss with respect to all weights using the chain rule, enabling gradient descent optimization.",
          "concepts": [
            "backpropagation",
            "gradient descent",
            "chain rule",
            "loss functions"
          ],
          "youtube_id": "Ilg3gGewQ5U",
          "video_title": "Backpropagation calculus | 3Blue1Brown",
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
      ]
