        {
          "title": "Optimization Algorithms",
          "slug": "optimization-algorithms",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Optimization Algorithms\n\n## Why Not Vanilla SGD?\n\nStandard SGD with a fixed learning rate has a fundamental problem: the optimal learning rate differs across parameters. Weights that receive sparse gradients (e.g., embeddings for rare words) need larger updates; weights with consistent large gradients need smaller steps to avoid overshooting.\n\nModern optimizers address this by **adapting the learning rate per parameter**.\n\n## SGD with Momentum\n\nMomentum accelerates SGD in the relevant direction and dampens oscillations:\n\n```\nv_t = β · v_{t-1} + (1 − β) · g_t\nW ← W − η · v_t\n```\n\nThe velocity **v** accumulates a moving average of gradients. With β=0.9, the optimizer \"remembers\" the last ~10 gradient directions, smoothing out noisy updates.\n\n```python\noptimizer = torch.optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.01, momentum=0.9)\n```\n\n## RMSProp\n\nRMSProp adapts learning rates by dividing by the root mean square of recent gradients:\n\n```\ns_t = β · s_{t-1} + (1 − β) · g_t²\nW ← W − (η / √(s_t + ε)) · g_t\n```\n\nParameters with large recent gradients get smaller effective learning rates. The ε (epsilon) term prevents division by zero.\n\n## Adam: Adaptive Moment Estimation\n\nAdam combines momentum (first moment) with RMSProp (second moment):\n\n```\nm_t = β₁ · m_{t-1} + (1 − β₁) · g_t          # first moment (mean)\nv_t = β₂ · v_{t-1} + (1 − β₂) · g_t²          # second moment (variance)\n\nm̂_t = m_t / (1 − β₁ᵗ)                          # bias-corrected\nv̂_t = v_t / (1 − β₂ᵗ)                          # bias-corrected\n\nW ← W − η · m̂_t / (√v̂_t + ε)\n```\n\nDefault hyperparameters: β₁=0.9, β₂=0.999, ε=1e-8, η=1e-3.\n\n```python\noptimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=1e-3, betas=(0.9, 0.999))\n```\n\n## AdamW: Adam with Decoupled Weight Decay\n\nStandard Adam applies L2 regularization incorrectly (it gets absorbed into the adaptive learning rate). **AdamW** decouples weight decay from gradient updates:\n\n```\nW ← W · (1 − η · λ) − η · m̂_t / (√v̂_t + ε)\n```\n\nAdamW is the default optimizer for training Transformers/LLMs.\n\n```python\noptimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=1e-4, weight_decay=0.01)\n```\n\n## Learning Rate Schedules\n\nA fixed learning rate is suboptimal. Common schedules:\n\n**Cosine Annealing**: Smoothly decays lr following a cosine curve — high initially for fast progress, low near the end for fine refinement.\n\n```python\nscheduler = torch.optim.lr_scheduler.CosineAnnealingLR(optimizer, T_max=100)\n```\n\n**Linear Warmup + Cosine Decay** (used in LLM training):\n```python\nfrom transformers import get_cosine_schedule_with_warmup\nscheduler = get_cosine_schedule_with_warmup(\n    optimizer, num_warmup_steps=500, num_training_steps=10000\n)\n```\n\nWarmup is crucial for Transformer training: starting with a large lr causes instability in the early layers.\n\n## Gradient Clipping\n\nExploding gradients (the opposite of vanishing) can crash training. Clip the global gradient norm:\n\n```python\ntorch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), max_norm=1.0)\n```\n\nThis is standard practice when training RNNs and Transformers.\n\n## Practical Tips\n\n- **Default choice**: AdamW with lr=1e-4 for fine-tuning, 1e-3 for training from scratch\n- **Learning rate finder**: Train for one epoch while increasing lr exponentially; pick the rate just before loss explodes\n- **Batch size matters**: Larger batches → can use larger lr (linear scaling rule)\n- Always use gradient clipping with Transformers\n",
          "summary": "Modern optimizers like Adam adaptively tune learning rates per parameter, dramatically accelerating training of deep networks.",
          "concepts": [
            "Adam",
            "SGD",
            "momentum",
            "learning rate schedules",
            "weight decay"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Regularization & Normalization",
          "slug": "regularization",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Regularization & Normalization\n\n## The Overfitting Problem\n\nA model with millions of parameters can perfectly memorize training data — outputting near-zero loss while failing catastrophically on new examples. This is **overfitting**: the model learns noise and spurious correlations instead of generalizable patterns.\n\nRegularization techniques constrain the model to learn simpler, more robust representations.\n\n## L1 and L2 Regularization\n\nAdd a penalty on weight magnitude to the loss function:\n\n- **L2 (Ridge)**: λ Σ wᵢ² — penalizes large weights, encourages small distributed weights\n- **L1 (Lasso)**: λ Σ |wᵢ| — encourages sparse weights (many exact zeros)\n\n```python\n# L2 via weight_decay in AdamW\noptimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=1e-4, weight_decay=1e-2)\n\n# Manual L2 loss\nl2_loss = sum(p.pow(2).sum() for p in model.parameters())\ntotal_loss = task_loss + lambda_ * l2_loss\n```\n\n## Dropout\n\nDropout randomly **zeroes out** neurons during training with probability *p*:\n\n```python\nself.dropout = nn.Dropout(p=0.1)\nx = self.dropout(x)  # training: zeros ~10% of activations\n                     # inference: scales by (1-p), no dropout\n```\n\n**Intuition**: By preventing neurons from co-adapting (relying on specific other neurons), dropout forces the network to learn redundant representations. It's equivalent to training an ensemble of 2ⁿ different networks simultaneously.\n\nTypical values: p=0.1–0.3 for Transformers, p=0.5 for fully-connected layers.\n\n## Batch Normalization\n\nBatch Norm (BN) normalizes activations across the batch dimension, then rescales with learned parameters γ and β:\n\n```\nμ_B = (1/m) Σ xᵢ              # batch mean\nσ²_B = (1/m) Σ (xᵢ − μ_B)²  # batch variance\nx̂ᵢ = (xᵢ − μ_B) / √(σ²_B + ε)  # normalize\nyᵢ = γ x̂ᵢ + β               # scale and shift\n```\n\n```python\nself.bn = nn.BatchNorm1d(hidden_dim)\nx = self.bn(self.linear(x))\n```\n\n**Why BN helps**:\n1. Reduces **internal covariate shift** — later layers see stable input distributions as earlier layers change\n2. Acts as a regularizer (noise from batch statistics)\n3. Allows higher learning rates\n4. Smooths the loss landscape\n\n**Limitation**: Doesn't work well with small batch sizes or in sequence models (batch statistics are ill-defined).\n\n## Layer Normalization\n\nLayer Norm normalizes across the **feature dimension** (not the batch dimension), making it batch-size independent:\n\n```\nμ = (1/H) Σ xᵢ    # mean over features\nσ = √((1/H) Σ (xᵢ − μ)²)\nx̂ = (x − μ) / (σ + ε)\ny = γ x̂ + β\n```\n\n```python\nself.ln = nn.LayerNorm(hidden_dim)\n```\n\nLayer Norm is the standard choice for **Transformers** because it works well for variable-length sequences and any batch size.\n\n## Data Augmentation\n\nArtificially expand the training set by applying label-preserving transformations:\n\n```python\nfrom torchvision import transforms\naugment = transforms.Compose([\n    transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),\n    transforms.RandomCrop(32, padding=4),\n    transforms.ColorJitter(brightness=0.2),\n])\n```\n\nFor NLP: random token deletion, synonym replacement, back-translation.\n\n## Practical Guidelines\n\n| Technique | When to Use |\n|-----------|-------------|\n| Weight decay (L2) | Almost always; set to 0.01–0.1 |\n| Dropout | FC layers, attention; skip for BN layers |\n| BatchNorm | CNNs, MLPs with large batches |\n| LayerNorm | Transformers, RNNs |\n| Data augmentation | Small datasets; always for vision |\n\nThe best regularization is often **more data** — augmentation is a cheap proxy for this.\n",
          "summary": "Regularization techniques prevent overfitting by constraining model complexity, while normalization layers stabilize training dynamics.",
          "concepts": [
            "dropout",
            "batch normalization",
            "layer normalization",
            "weight decay",
            "data augmentation"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
