        {
          "title": "CNNs & Representation Learning",
          "slug": "cnns-representation-learning",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# CNNs & Representation Learning\n\n## From Pixels to Features\n\nFeeding raw pixel values into a fully-connected network is wasteful — an image is not a flat vector. A 256×256 RGB image has 196,608 inputs; a single hidden layer with 1,000 neurons means ~200 million weights. Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) exploit the spatial structure of images using three key ideas: **local connectivity**, **parameter sharing**, and **translation equivariance**.\n\n## The Convolution Operation\n\nA **convolutional layer** slides a small filter (kernel) across the input, computing dot products at each position to produce a **feature map**:\n\n```python\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\nconv = nn.Conv2d(\n    in_channels=3,    # RGB input\n    out_channels=64,  # 64 different filters\n    kernel_size=3,    # 3x3 filter\n    padding=1         # preserve spatial dimensions\n)\n```\n\nEach filter learns to detect a specific pattern — edges, textures, corners. Stacking convolutional layers builds a **hierarchy of representations**: edges → textures → parts → objects.\n\n## Pooling and Downsampling\n\n**Max pooling** reduces spatial dimensions by taking the maximum value in each local region, making features invariant to small translations:\n\n```python\npool = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)  # halves spatial dims\n```\n\nA typical CNN alternates convolution + ReLU → pooling, progressively reducing spatial size while increasing the number of feature channels.\n\n## The ImageNet Moment\n\nIn 2012, **AlexNet** won the ImageNet challenge by a dramatic margin — slashing the error rate from 26% to 16%. This was the moment deep learning went from academic curiosity to industry revolution.\n\n| Model | Year | Key Innovation |\n|-------|------|----------------|\n| **AlexNet** | 2012 | Deep CNN + GPU training, dropout |\n| **VGG** | 2014 | Deeper networks (16-19 layers), small 3×3 filters |\n| **GoogLeNet** | 2014 | Inception modules, multiple filter sizes in parallel |\n| **ResNet** | 2015 | Residual connections — enabling 100+ layer networks |\n\n## Residual Connections (Skip Connections)\n\nResNet's key insight: instead of learning a mapping H(x), learn the **residual** F(x) = H(x) − x:\n\n```\noutput = F(x) + x    # skip connection\n```\n\nThis lets gradients flow directly through the skip path, solving vanishing gradients for very deep networks. Residual connections are now used everywhere — including every Transformer.\n\n```python\nclass ResidualBlock(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, channels):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(channels, channels, 3, padding=1)\n        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(channels, channels, 3, padding=1)\n        self.bn1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(channels)\n        self.bn2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(channels)\n\n    def forward(self, x):\n        residual = x\n        out = F.relu(self.bn1(self.conv1(x)))\n        out = self.bn2(self.conv2(out))\n        return F.relu(out + residual)\n```\n\n## Why CNNs Matter for the ML Journey\n\nCNNs introduced ideas that pervade all modern architectures: **hierarchical feature learning**, **residual connections** (reused in Transformers), and **pre-training on large datasets** (ImageNet as the predecessor to LLM pre-training). While Vision Transformers (ViTs) have largely replaced CNNs at the frontier, their architectural innovations shaped everything that followed.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Stanford CS231n: Convolutional Neural Networks for Visual Recognition](https://cs231n.github.io/convolutional-networks/) — the gold standard introduction to CNNs, with excellent visualizations.\n- [3Blue1Brown: But what is a convolution?](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KuXjwB4LzSA) — a visual exploration of the convolution operation and why it appears everywhere in deep learning.\n",
          "summary": "CNNs exploit the spatial structure of images through convolutions, pooling, and residual connections — architectural ideas that shaped all modern deep learning.",
          "concepts": [
            "convolution",
            "feature maps",
            "pooling",
            "residual connections",
            "ImageNet"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "RNNs, LSTMs & Sequence Modeling",
          "slug": "rnns-sequence-modeling",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# RNNs, LSTMs & Sequence Modeling\n\n## The Problem with Sequences\n\nFeed-forward networks process fixed-size inputs — but language, music, and time series are **sequential**. The meaning of a word depends on what came before it. \"Bank\" means something different in \"river bank\" vs \"bank account\", and that context can be arbitrarily far back.\n\nRNNs handle this by maintaining a **hidden state** that acts as memory.\n\n## Recurrent Neural Networks\n\nAt each timestep *t*, an RNN takes the current input **xₜ** and the previous hidden state **hₜ₋₁**, producing a new hidden state:\n\n```\nhₜ = tanh(Wₕ hₜ₋₁ + Wₓ xₜ + b)\n```\n\nThe same weights **Wₕ** and **Wₓ** are shared across all timesteps — the network \"unrolls\" through time.\n\n```python\nrnn = nn.RNN(input_size=128, hidden_size=256, num_layers=1, batch_first=True)\noutput, h_n = rnn(x)  # output: all hidden states, h_n: final hidden state\n```\n\n## The Vanishing Gradient Strikes Again\n\nDuring backpropagation through time (BPTT), gradients are multiplied by **Wₕ** at each step. Over long sequences (50+ tokens), gradients either **vanish** (|Wₕ| < 1) or **explode** (|Wₕ| > 1). In practice, vanilla RNNs can only learn dependencies spanning about 10-20 timesteps.\n\n## LSTMs: Learning to Remember and Forget\n\n**Long Short-Term Memory** networks (Hochreiter & Schmidhuber, 1997) solve this with a **cell state** — a highway that information flows through unchanged, plus **gates** that control what to add or remove:\n\n- **Forget gate**: What to erase from cell state: fₜ = σ(Wf[hₜ₋₁, xₜ])\n- **Input gate**: What new information to store: iₜ = σ(Wi[hₜ₋₁, xₜ])\n- **Output gate**: What to output: oₜ = σ(Wo[hₜ₋₁, xₜ])\n\nThe cell state update:\n\n```\nC̃ₜ = tanh(Wc[hₜ₋₁, xₜ])     # candidate values\nCₜ = fₜ ⊙ Cₜ₋₁ + iₜ ⊙ C̃ₜ   # update cell state\nhₜ = oₜ ⊙ tanh(Cₜ)           # output hidden state\n```\n\nThe key insight: the cell state **Cₜ** can carry information across many timesteps with only element-wise operations — no matrix multiplication, so gradients don't vanish.\n\n```python\nlstm = nn.LSTM(input_size=128, hidden_size=256, num_layers=2, batch_first=True)\noutput, (h_n, c_n) = lstm(x)  # c_n is the cell state\n```\n\n## GRUs: A Simpler Alternative\n\n**Gated Recurrent Units** merge the forget and input gates into a single \"update gate\" and combine cell and hidden state. Fewer parameters, comparable performance in practice.\n\n## Sequence-to-Sequence & The Bottleneck\n\nFor tasks like translation, an **encoder** LSTM reads the source sentence and compresses it into a final hidden state, which a **decoder** LSTM uses to generate the output token by token.\n\nThe critical problem: the entire source sentence — regardless of length — must be compressed into a **single fixed-size vector**. For long sentences, this is catastrophically lossy. This fundamental limitation motivated the invention of **attention** — the subject of the next module.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Understanding LSTM Networks](https://colah.github.io/posts/2015-08-Understanding-LSTMs/) by Chris Olah — the clearest explanation of LSTM gates, with beautiful diagrams. A must-read.\n",
          "summary": "RNNs process sequential data by maintaining hidden state across timesteps, while LSTMs use gating mechanisms to learn long-range dependencies without vanishing gradients.",
          "concepts": [
            "recurrent neural networks",
            "hidden state",
            "LSTM",
            "gating mechanisms",
            "sequence-to-sequence",
            "vanishing gradients"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
