      "title": "The Road to Transformers",
      "order_index": 3,
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "Word Embeddings & Representation",
          "slug": "word-embeddings",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Word Embeddings & Representation\n\n## The Representation Problem\n\nHow do you feed words into a neural network? The naive approach is **one-hot encoding**: each word is a vector with a 1 at its index and 0s everywhere else. For a vocabulary of 50,000 words, \"cat\" might be [0, 0, ..., 1, ..., 0] — a 50,000-dimensional vector.\n\nProblems: these vectors are **sparse** (mostly zeros, wasteful), **high-dimensional**, and worst of all, they encode no relationships — the distance between \"cat\" and \"kitten\" is the same as between \"cat\" and \"uranium\".\n\n## Word2Vec: Learning Meaning from Context\n\n**Word2Vec** (Mikolov et al., 2013) learns dense, low-dimensional vectors (typically 100-300 dimensions) from the distributional hypothesis: *words that appear in similar contexts have similar meanings*.\n\nTwo training approaches:\n\n- **Skip-gram**: Given a word, predict its surrounding context words. \"The [cat] sat on\" → predict \"the\", \"sat\", \"on\" from \"cat\".\n- **CBOW (Continuous Bag of Words)**: Given context words, predict the center word. \"The ___ sat on\" → predict \"cat\".\n\nThe magic: training on millions of sentences, the model learns that \"cat\" and \"kitten\" appear in similar contexts — so their vectors end up close together.\n\n## Embedding Arithmetic\n\nThe most striking property of Word2Vec embeddings is that they capture **semantic relationships as vector operations**:\n\n```\nking − man + woman ≈ queen\nParis − France + Italy ≈ Rome\nwalked − walking + swimming ≈ swam\n```\n\nThese aren't hand-coded rules — they emerge naturally from training on raw text.\n\n## GloVe: Global Vectors\n\n**GloVe** (Pennington et al., 2014) takes a different approach: instead of predicting context words, it factorizes the global **word co-occurrence matrix**. If \"ice\" and \"cold\" co-occur frequently, their vectors are trained to reflect that. GloVe captures similar relationships as Word2Vec but uses global statistics rather than local context windows.\n\n## Using Pre-trained Embeddings\n\nIn practice, you rarely train embeddings from scratch. Pre-trained embeddings are used as the first layer:\n\n```python\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\nembedding = nn.Embedding(vocab_size, embed_dim)\n\n# Load pre-trained weights\nembedding.weight = nn.Parameter(pretrained_vectors)\n\n# Optional: freeze embeddings\nembedding.weight.requires_grad = False\n```\n\n## The Limitation: Static Representations\n\nWord2Vec and GloVe assign **one vector per word** regardless of context. The word \"bank\" gets the same embedding whether it means a financial institution or a river bank.\n\nThis limitation drove the development of **contextual embeddings** — models like ELMo (2018) that produce different representations for the same word in different contexts by running it through a deep bidirectional LSTM.\n\nThe Transformer architecture would take this even further: every token's representation is fully context-dependent, computed through self-attention over the entire sequence.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [The Illustrated Word2Vec](https://jalammar.github.io/illustrated-word2vec/) by Jay Alammar — an excellent visual walkthrough of how word embeddings are trained, with intuitive diagrams that make the math click.\n",
          "summary": "Word embeddings like Word2Vec and GloVe represent words as dense vectors that capture semantic meaning, enabling neural networks to work with language.",
          "concepts": [
            "word embeddings",
            "Word2Vec",
            "GloVe",
            "distributional hypothesis",
            "contextual embeddings"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
